<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-106-964  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 106 964.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Engineering  Dec 1989 v8 n12 p56(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Peripherals: add-on hardware is necessary for CAD. (computer-aideddesign)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mills, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A variety of data entry, hardcopy output, memory and specializedgraphics hardware are required to enable computers to handlecomputer-aided design (CAD) applications.andP;  Data entry devices mayinclude mice, digitizers and tablets, scanners, complete scanningsystems, joysticks, lightpens, and trackballs.andP;  Hardcopy outputunits are either vector devices (pen or electrostatic plotters) orraster devices (thermal, electrostatic, dot matrix, ink jet,direct imaging and laser printers, and film recorders).andP;  Thevariety of specialized graphics hardware for CAD includes graphicsadapters and monitors, X terminals and vector refresh and rastersystems.andP;  Memory hardware may be either integrated circuits formain memory or such mass storage devices as floppy, fixed hard,optical, or removable hard disks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     PeripheralsGraphics SystemsCompatible HardwareHardware SelectionComputer-Aided DesignApplications.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartphotograph.andO;Caption:   Plotting with raster devices is faster than with traditional penplotters. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>